-- Bitwise / shift emitters. The stack convention pops the right operand into
-- rcx (0x59) and the left into rax (0x58), computes lhs OP rhs into rax, then
-- pushes rax (0x50). Each is 6 bytes (matching the add/sub layout arm); bnot is
-- 5. For shifts the count is already in rcx (so cl), and `shl/shr rax,cl` reads
-- the count from cl, which x86 masks to 6 bits for 64-bit operands -- exactly
-- the `& 63` the C oracle and the meta-circular VM use.
func nc_emit_band(buf):
    do append(buf, 89)
    do append(buf, 88)
    do append(buf, 72)
    do append(buf, 33)
    do append(buf, 200)
    do append(buf, 80)
    return buf
end

